<subSubSection id="18FD10D73DE7E314C2209E5AA4F8DAB4" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="63C1A4868A5D4EF33FF8BB6650BCFF20" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E6953A70A1E51B748CCD3059BBB1101B" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
Brazil (
<normalizedToken id="B857C1E122C4095A07EFE7ECE14C3754" originalValue="ParanÃ¡">Parana</normalizedToken>
, Rio Grande do Sul, Santa Catarina).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C28B12723A5E32381854728C86FE229B" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
<emphasis id="8AF979975B7AC8CF5A6662253F9FD870" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Biology.</emphasis>
This is the first record of 
<taxonomicName id="F5BC6EB2946922A9BC1FB68122358A1C" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Pompilidae</taxonomicName>
as a host of 
<taxonomicName id="A009E852C2CFC096F140B6C78A84E4E6" authority="AndrÃ©, 1905" authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Xystromutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xystromutilla" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2A608249DD96B1E5A6612F68998797A3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Xystromutilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the Araucaria forest fragments, 66 trap-nests of 
<taxonomicName id="4819FE97581E8F6CD75052A178FAA20A" authorityName="Dreisbach" authorityYear="1963" class="Hexapoda" family="Pompilidae" genus="Auplopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Auplopus subaurarius" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subaurarius">
<emphasis id="8179316DF2A7DE3ED2A00D57BDB4C269" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Auplopus subaurarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Dreisbach were examined. Of these nests, 
<taxonomicName id="035E52DE4261F1620089C7862FAB972D" genus="X." lsidName="X. bucki" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="species" species="bucki">
<emphasis id="E500E679301311A8D91D58E8F7AEA700" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">X. bucki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
parasitized three of them, all of which were in bamboo, 1.3 cm in diameter and 18.2 cm in length. One of the nests had nine cells, six of which were parasitized by 
<taxonomicName id="693DD9D5FCBB418C59B76D739647F39F" authority="AndrÃ©, 1905" authorityName="Andre" authorityYear="1905" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Xystromutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xystromutilla" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="5F9406227DB954F78B4675F7A4AC9085" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Xystromutilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(five males and one female emerged) and two by 
<taxonomicName id="3C49386DA0230A2585A9501B98BD5812" authorityName="Viereck" authorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Photocryptus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Photocryptus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9E885A2AA854B65E347580C59C921A97" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Photocryptus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName id="7F265571418805A0C5B366BF50773A44" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Ichneumonidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="C9D5FC12885CFB075F665AAA9EB99596" authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1837" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cryptinae">Cryptinae</taxonomicName>
). The other two parasitized nests contained one cell each, from which emerged a male and a female. Therefore, six males and two females emerged in total from the nests. The males were larger bodied with average head width 0.3 mm (n = 6; SD = 0.01 mm) and the females 0.2 mm (n = 2; SD = 0.06 mm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8F341F7D42C1417CFDE0422C13E13168" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">
We found in 
<taxonomicName id="EED545F80A52D998F919665FFA3E9343" authority="AndrÃ©, 1905" authorityName="Suarez" authorityYear="1960" class="Insecta" family="Mutillidae" genus="Xystromutilla" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xystromutilla bucki" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bucki">
<emphasis id="7CE623F00AD470A1C4D304213B24D15D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="73">Xystromutilla bucki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that the average time between nest collection and adult wasp emergence, for seven of the eight specimens reared, was 265 days (n = 7; SD = 4.2 days), with immatures exhibiting diapause at the prepupal stage (6 males, 1 female). Only one female (from the one-celled nest) did not enter into diapause, but rather emerged 11 days after nest collection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
